2026-04-16 12:18:12 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module switch contacts / series path between Control Input (+) and Control Output (+)', 'internal return path between Control Input (−) and Control Output (−) within control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The power‑supply output is correct (+12 V on the positive line, 0 V on the negative), and this correct polarity reaches the control‑module input, as verified by measurements. However, with the switch in the ON (closed) position, both control‑module output cables (to the load) remain at 0 V, and the load‑module input also sits at 0 V. This means that the +12 V present at the control‑module input is not being passed through to the output, even when the switch is commanded closed.\n\nSince cable polarity and inter‑module connections have been confirmed correct, the only remaining place where the circuit can be opened (or both lines tied to 0 V) is inside the control module itself. The most likely fault is a failure in the switch contacts or in the series conduction path that should connect Control Input (+) to Control Output (+) when the switch is ON. A break or mis‑wiring in this path would leave the output floating, and due to internal circuitry and measurement reference it appears as 0 V. A similar issue may exist on the negative return path (Control Input (−) to Control Output (−)).\n\nTherefore the root cause is an internal fault in the control module—specifically in the switch or its associated series wiring—which prevents the input supply from reaching the output, so the lamp never receives voltage and cannot turn on.'
